    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-01-23T03:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-01-23T01:34:00-05:00" n="369"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d369">
                <head>369. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d369fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Records of
                        the Office of the Counselor, Entry 5339, Box 7, Soviet Union. Secret; <gloss
                            target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>. The meeting took place at the Foreign
                        Ministry in the Tolstoy House. The full text of the memorandum of
                        conversation is scheduled for publication in <ref target="frus1969-76v16">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume XVI, Soviet
                            Union, August 1974–December 1976</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1976-01-23T09:34:00+03:00" to="1976-01-23T11:45:00+03:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">January 23, 1976, 9:34–11:45
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR1">
                            <hi rend="italic">USSR</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Andrei A. Gromyko</persName>, Member of
                                the Politburo of the Central Committee of the <gloss
                                    target="#t_CPSU1">CPSU</gloss>; Minister of Foreign Affairs of
                                the <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>Vasiliy V. Kuznetsov, First Deputy Minister of Foreign
                                Affairs</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_KGM1">Georgiy M. Korniyenko</persName>, Deputy
                                Minister of Foreign Affairs</item>
                            <item>Anatoliy F. Dobrynin, Ambassador to the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                    >U.S.</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MVG1">Vasiliy G. Makarov</persName>, Chef de
                                Cabinet to the Foreign Minister</item>
                            <item>V.G. Komplektov, Acting Chief of <gloss target="#t_USA1"
                                    >USA</gloss> Dept., <gloss target="#t_MFA1">MFA</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName>Valerian V. Mikhailov</persName>, Deputy Chief of <gloss
                                    target="#t_USA1">USA</gloss> Dept., <gloss target="#t_MFA1"
                                    >MFA</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>Oleg Grinevskiy, Deputy Chief of Middle East Dept., <gloss
                                    target="#t_MFA1">MFA</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>Oleg M. Sokolov, Chief of International Affairs, <gloss
                                    target="#t_USA1">USA</gloss> Dept., <gloss target="#t_MFA1"
                                    >MFA</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SVM1">Viktor M. Sukhodrev</persName>,
                                Counselor, Second European Dept., <gloss target="#t_MFA1"
                                    >MFA</gloss> (Interpreter)</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <pb facs="1122" n="1087" xml:id="pg_1087"/>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">
                            <hi rend="italic">U.S.</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>,
                                Secretary of State</item>
                            <item>Amb. <persName corresp="#p_SWJJ1">Walter J. Stoessel,
                                    Jr</persName>., Ambassador to the <gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                                    >USSR</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SHH1">Helmut Sonnenfeldt</persName>, Counselor
                                of the Department</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_HWG1">William G. Hyland</persName>, Deputy
                                Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_HAA4">Arthur A. Hartman</persName>, Assistant
                                Secretary for European Affairs</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName>Arthur R. Day</persName>, Deputy Assistant Secretary for
                                Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName>Edward F. Fugit</persName>, Country Officer, Angola</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_RPW1">Peter W. Rodman</persName>, <gloss
                                    target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Staff</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECTS</head>
                    <item>Middle East; Angola; Japan; China; Limitation of New Weapons of Mass
                        Destruction; PNE Negotiation; <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of matters other than <gloss target="#t_MBFR1"
                        >MBFR</gloss>.]</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">
                        <hi rend="italic">MBFR</hi>
                    </gloss>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: On the proposal last night
                    with respect to Mutual and Balanced Force Reductions,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d369fn2">See <ref target="#d368">Document 368</ref>.</note> do you
                    have the number from which the two-to-three percent is to be calculated?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>: The General Secretary set out
                    our view of principle, and they give you the line along which we are thinking
                    and which will be set out in detail. And when we submit the specific proposals
                    after discussions resume in Vienna, we will have specific considerations to set
                    forth, and we are now giving deliberation to that aspect.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: Because we can’t give a reply
                    until we know what your number is.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>: We are now giving thought to
                    that aspect and we feel in the very near future we will be able to give a
                    definite reply. It certainly would be a good thing to give a new lease on life
                    to the work in Vienna.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: We will study it carefully.
                    I’m not too optimistic, as I told the General Secretary.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>: So you are not taking away
                    optimism on this?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: I’ll have to see your concrete
                    proposal before I make a final judgment.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>: All right. As long as you don’t
                    carry away pessimism from Moscow on this question.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: I think we should make
                    progress this year on mutual force reductions.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>: That would be good. China will
                    certainly have a lot to blame us for. If there is success. Mostly us.</p>
                <pb facs="1123" n="1088" xml:id="pg_1088"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: China will certainly be very
                    angry. China will certainly be very angry if there is success in <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss>.<note n="3" xml:id="d369fn3">On January 25,
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> reported to President
                            <persName corresp="#p_FGR1">Ford</persName> on his visit to Moscow in a
                        conversation at the Oval Office. A memorandum of their conversation reads in
                        part: “President: Anything on <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>?
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: Yes. They rejected
                        Option III. They proposed a 3% cut in overall forces, taken from <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> and Soviet forces.” (Library of Congress,
                        Manuscript Division, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>
                        Papers, Box CL 283, Memoranda of Conversation, Presidential File)</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of matters other than <gloss target="#t_MBFR1"
                        >MBFR</gloss>.]</p>
            </div>
        </body>
